Hi guys! I was a huge fan of `req.param`, used it all the time and didn't care much. Well, until I suddenly realized that it doesn't always return strings (as documentation states), but it can also return arrays, if query or body parsers caught the same parameter twice.

This renders most code like `req.param('email', '').trim().toLowerCase()` broken, and checking _each and every_ parameter with `Array.isArray` is pretty much an overkill.

I'd suggest that the default behavior of `req.param` would be like this:

```
req.param = function(name, defaultValue){
  var params = this.params || {};
  var body = this.body || {};
  var query = this.query || {};
  var value = (params.hasOwnProperty(name) && params[name]) ||
    body[name] || query[name];
  return Array.isArray(value) ? value[0] : (value || defaultValue);
};
```

And also adding a method like that:

```
req.list = function(name){
  var params = this.params || {};
  var body = this.body || {};
  var query = this.query || {};
  var value = (params.hasOwnProperty(name) && params[name]) ||
    body[name] || query[name];
  if (null == value) return [];
  return Array.isArray(value) ? value : [value];
};
```

You see, the second one always returns arrays, even if parameter isn't provided at all, which is totally ok if you expect the N-arity input.

I'm not sure about the `req.list` name, though. Also not sure whether this breaking change should be done the hard way — by reimplementing the `req.param` — or by introducing the third method and leaving `req.param` as is.

