Suppose ./routes/index.js defines an object 

``` javascript
foobar = { foo: "a", bar: [1, 2]};
```

Then suppose we have two routes:

``` javascript
exports.one = function(req,res){
  // All four outputs (2 to console, two rendered as HTML) should give the full 'foobar' object.
  // And this is exactly what we get.
  res.locals.foobar = foobar;
  console.log('Route says, foobar is ' + JSON.stringify(res.locals.foobar));
  res.locals.raboof = foobar;
  console.log('Route says, raboof is ' + JSON.stringify(res.locals.raboof));
  res.render('view');
};

exports.two = function(req,res){
  // All four outputs (2 to console, two rendered as HTML) should give the 'foo' member.
  // The console outputs are as expected.  One HTML rendering matches; the other is inconsistent.
  // The inconsistent one is the one which uses the same name (foobar) in both scopes. 
  res.locals.foobar = foobar.foo;   // same name in both scopes -> behaves unexpectedly
  console.log('Route says, foobar is ' + JSON.stringify(res.locals.foobar));
  res.locals.raboof = foobar.foo;   // different names -> behaves as expected
  console.log('Route says, raboof is ' + JSON.stringify(res.locals.raboof));
  res.render('view');
};
```

We see that node knows very well what we intended, as confirmed by the console outputs for both routes.  And when jade renders the view for route 'one' we see the expected output -- the full 'foobar' object.  But when jade renders the view for route 'two' we get a surprise (at least I did).  Although the console output clearly shows that we expect just the foo component of foobar, the rendered view matches the console (as intended) only if we do _not_ reuse the module-scoped name 'foobar' in the function's res.locals.\* scope.  If we _do_ reuse the name, we get a surprise when the rendered HTML gives the full foobar object from the module scope, regardless of the value assigned via res.locals.foobar = whatever.

I suspect this has something to do with res.locals having become a function in express 3.x but I have to say that this is _extremely_ surprising behavior and can easily lead to some very hard to find bugs.  This got me in a real application and I wasted an embarrassing amount of time in disbelief before building a test app.  Even if this behavior can be rationalized, is it really a good thing?

